                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1775" notAfter="1838">
                        <p>Probably repaired and rebound in the Indian subcontinent, possibly for
                           former owner <persName role="fmo" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/35362797"
                              key="person_35362797"> Jonathan Scott (1574–1829)</persName>.</p>
                        <p>Resewn at 2 stations, unsupported, edges trimmed, with twined chevron
                           endbands in yellow and green silk at <locus from="Head" to="Head"
                              >head</locus> and <locus from="Tail" to="Tail">tail</locus>. Covered
                           in full maroon goatskin <material>leather</material>, tight-backed, over
                           pasteboards, flush-cut with the edges, but without a lap (Type III
                           binding per Déroche), with internal doublures of the same
                              <material>leather</material>, their excess widths adhered as hinges
                           connecting to the first and last flyleaves to the cover, with strips of
                           paper applied over top to disguise the joins.</p>
